         <abstract>
            <p>This paper applies multiperiod portfolio theory to the construction and rebalancing of portfolios composed of U.S. stocks, corporate bonds, government bonds, and a risk-free asset, with small stocks included as a separate investment vehicle. Probability assessments are based on the past, joint empirical distribution. Our principal findings are (1) small stocks, while totally ignored at times, entered even the most risk-averse portfolios most of the time and (2) small stocks, when chosen, tended to replace common stocks, except in the 1970s and early 1980s, when they were primarily held in lieu of the risk-free asset.</p>
         </abstract>
